		By: Spade		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.com/goals-systems#comment-14166</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Spade]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 20 Jan 2015 23:55:56 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=5344#comment-14166</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[&quot;For a minute or two, I thought about doing my final set. Then, I reminded myself that I plan to do this for the rest of my life and decided to call it a day.&quot;

So, what you&#039;re actually saying is that doing this for the rest of your life is your long-term goal, and you&#039;re staying focused on that instead of being distracted by potential short-term goals.

You&#039;ve argued persuasively, then, for the value of long-term goals over short-term goals:

1) You&#039;ve committed to a process that serves your long-term goals.
2) Your focus on the long term releases you from looking for immediate short-term results.
3) Feedback loops help you make adjustments that keep your processes pointed toward your long-term goals.

Yes, systems are good for actually making progress. But you can&#039;t really measure &quot;progress&quot; without some kind of goal that you&#039;re either getting closer to or further away from.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>&#8220;For a minute or two, I thought about doing my final set. Then, I reminded myself that I plan to do this for the rest of my life and decided to call it a day.&#8221;</p>
<p>So, what you&#8217;re actually saying is that doing this for the rest of your life is your long-term goal, and you&#8217;re staying focused on that instead of being distracted by potential short-term goals.</p>
<p>You&#8217;ve argued persuasively, then, for the value of long-term goals over short-term goals:</p>
<p>1) You&#8217;ve committed to a process that serves your long-term goals.<br />
2) Your focus on the long term releases you from looking for immediate short-term results.<br />
3) Feedback loops help you make adjustments that keep your processes pointed toward your long-term goals.</p>
<p>Yes, systems are good for actually making progress. But you can&#8217;t really measure &#8220;progress&#8221; without some kind of goal that you&#8217;re either getting closer to or further away from.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
