		<title>
		By: Roy		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.com/goals-systems#comment-14093</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Roy]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 16 Jan 2015 04:54:44 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=5344#comment-14093</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[I don&#039;t think I could disagree with an article more:

Goals reduce your current happiness.
Goals don&#039;t define my happiness. In fact, happiness is fleeting. I choose to have Joy.  Goals give me a target.

Goals are strangely at odds with long-term progress.
If this is you, then you aren&#039;t planning properly.  You need 1 month, 6 month, 1 year, 5 year, 10 year, 20 year goals etc, etc.

Goals suggest that you can control things that you have no control over.
Yes, I can predict the future, I do it every day. If I decide I&#039;m going to grow my business by 10%, then I&#039;m going to grow my business by 10%. Where ever you put your focus is where you see results.  Using my example, if I focus on growing my business, I&#039;ll talk to people about it, read books about it, watch videos about it and it will happen. Improving my systems will be a side effect of focusing on my goal. 

By focusing merely on systems you risk only focusing on the problems with your systems. Guess what? Your systems will NEVER be PERFECT so you could end up focusing on the &quot;how&quot; and never focusing on &quot;what&#039;s next?&quot;.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I don&#8217;t think I could disagree with an article more:</p>
<p>Goals reduce your current happiness.<br />
Goals don&#8217;t define my happiness. In fact, happiness is fleeting. I choose to have Joy.  Goals give me a target.</p>
<p>Goals are strangely at odds with long-term progress.<br />
If this is you, then you aren&#8217;t planning properly.  You need 1 month, 6 month, 1 year, 5 year, 10 year, 20 year goals etc, etc.</p>
<p>Goals suggest that you can control things that you have no control over.<br />
Yes, I can predict the future, I do it every day. If I decide I&#8217;m going to grow my business by 10%, then I&#8217;m going to grow my business by 10%. Where ever you put your focus is where you see results.  Using my example, if I focus on growing my business, I&#8217;ll talk to people about it, read books about it, watch videos about it and it will happen. Improving my systems will be a side effect of focusing on my goal. </p>
<p>By focusing merely on systems you risk only focusing on the problems with your systems. Guess what? Your systems will NEVER be PERFECT so you could end up focusing on the &#8220;how&#8221; and never focusing on &#8220;what&#8217;s next?&#8221;.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
